  "opinion": "As a nurse who has worked in healthcare settings for over 25 years, I've witnessed firsthand how deeply ingrained stereotypes about women and minorities in STEM can affect performance and confidence. Stereotype threat isn't just a theoretical concept—it's the quiet anxiety that whispers, 'You're not good enough' when you're in a room full of people who might assume you don't belong. For me, it's the moment a young woman in my clinic hesitates to ask questions because she fears being labeled 'not smart enough' for her field. I've seen this pattern play out in my own life when I was in college, where I felt pressured to prove myself in math classes because of the assumption that women aren't naturally good at it. Addressing stereotype threat isn't about fixing people—it's about changing the environment. I believe we should create spaces where everyone feels safe to make mistakes, like when I mentor students who are hesitant to speak up. This means implementing programs that highlight diverse role models in STEM and training educators to recognize unconscious bias. In my community, we've started small by hosting workshops where local women and people of color share their experiences in tech and science. It's not a quick fix, but it's a step toward ensuring that everyone has the opportunity to thrive without the weight of stereotypes holding them back. In the end, we need to foster a culture where intelligence is celebrated as a journey, not a fixed trait.",
